From: Alan Cox <alan@linux.intel.com>
Date: Thu, 3 May 2012 22:21:53 +0100
Subject: tty_lock: undo the old tty_lock use on the ctty
Git-commit: 3af502b96649ccb7462da73b0cca446c8384b155
Patch-mainline: 3.5-rc1
References: bsc#1179745 CVE-2020-29660 bsc#1182505

get_current_tty has its own consistent locking. That means a pile of the
tty lock cases are not needed. As get_current_tty also keeps a reference the
tty object lifetime means we can propogate the lock removal out.

[js] there is no tty_open_current_tty, so comments dropped

Signed-off-by: Alan Cox <alan@linux.intel.com>
Signed-off-by: Greg Kroah-Hartman <gregkh@linuxfoundation.org>
Signed-off-by: Jiri Slaby <jslaby@suse.cz>
---
 drivers/tty/tty_io.c |    5 +++--
 1 file changed, 3 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)

--- a/drivers/tty/tty_io.c
+++ b/drivers/tty/tty_io.c
@@ -856,10 +856,11 @@ void disassociate_ctty(int on_exit)
  */
 void no_tty(void)
 {
+	/* FIXME: Review locking here. The tty_lock never covered any race
+	   between a new association and proc_clear_tty but possible we need
+	   to protect against this anyway */
 	struct task_struct *tsk = current;
-	tty_lock();
 	disassociate_ctty(0);
-	tty_unlock();
 	proc_clear_tty(tsk);
 }
 
